[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You'll need the following packages:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3 numpy pandas scikit-learn matplotlib
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs AWS credentials configured (via environment variables, instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `es:ESHttpPost`, `es:ESHttpPut`, `es:ESHttpGet` (for OpenSearch k-NN index operations)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint` (for the embedding model endpoint, if using SageMaker)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject` (for embedding storage and batch outputs)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem` (for hybrid prediction results)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For this example, we build everything locally with scikit-learn first (kNN retrieval, clustering, novelty scoring), then show how you'd wire the vector search into Amazon OpenSearch Service via boto3. The local version lets you see the full pipeline without incurring AWS costs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Config and Constants
